## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Obsolete, never thrown by the runtime |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`catch`/`finally`, leak locks, and leave objects half-constructed.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// The delegate must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result re-throws as AggregateException, matching original behavior.
        return task.Result;
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async overload — preferred in modern code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage — Before vs After

```csharp
// ── .NET Framework (old) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowComputation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── .NET 8 (new) ──
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowComputation(ct),   // pass token into your work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ── .NET 8 async (preferred) ──
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowComputationAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **Cancellation is cooperative** — if `work` ignores the token, it keeps running silently after the timeout. Pass the token into every I/O call, `Task.Delay`, loop check, etc.

2. **Fire-and-forget leak** — unlike `Abort()`, a timed-out task continues on a thread-pool thread. If it holds resources (DB connections, file handles), you must observe the token to release them.

3. **Wrapping non-cancellable APIs** — if you *cannot* modify the work (e.g., third-party library with no token support), wrap it but understand the thread won't actually stop:

    ```csharp
    // Last resort — the work still runs to completion in the background!
    public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        var task = Task.Run(work);
        if (task.Wait(timeout))
            return task.Result;

        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout. " +
            "Warning: work continues in background.");
    }
    ```

4. **`AggregateException` unwrapping** — `Task.Result` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException` (matching your original code). If callers expect the inner exception directly, use `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` instead.
